## The Israelites and the Holy Land (12-26)

God took a covenant from the Children of Israel. He appointed **12 leaders** among them (one for each of the twelve tribes). He promised them: if you establish prayer, give charity, believe in My messengers, and support them, I will forgive you and admit you to gardens beneath which rivers flow.

Then He tells them: **enter the Holy Land**.

They refuse:

> *"O Moses, indeed within it are people of great strength, and we will never enter it until they leave. If they leave, then we will enter."* (22)

They're afraid of the people already living there. God promised them victory, but they don't trust the promise.

Only **two men** among them stand firm:

> *"Enter upon them through the gate, for when you enter it, you will be victorious. And upon God you should rely, if you are believers."* (23)

The rest still refuse: *"O Moses, we will never enter it, ever, as long as they are in it. So go, you and your Lord, and fight. We will be sitting right here."* (24)

God's punishment: **40 years of wandering** in the desert. They had a promised land and threw it away because they were too afraid to walk through the door.

The lesson is aimed at the Muslim community too: when God tells you to act, *act*. Fear and hesitation after a clear command is a form of disobedience.
